<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="767" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[806,1421,1516,1693]" pageId="8" pageNumber="767">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schockaert &amp; Curini-Galletti &amp; Ridder &amp; Volonterio &amp; Artois" authorityYear="2009" box="[831,997,1579,1600]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" genus="Serrula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="8" pageNumber="767" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="acuta">
<emphasis box="[831,997,1579,1600]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="767">Serrula acuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schockaert &amp; Curini-Galletti &amp; Ridder &amp; Volonterio &amp; Artois" authorityYear="2009" box="[1153,1240,1579,1600]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" genus="Serrula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="8" pageNumber="767" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1153,1240,1579,1600]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="767">Serrula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with a single seminal vesicle?; slender pointed needles that are 25-Mm long, and are 6-Mm wide at the base. No data on the living animal.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[188,722,961,983]" pageId="9" pageNumber="768" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[164,779,839,983]" box="[188,722,961,983]" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schockaert &amp; Curini-Galletti &amp; Ridder &amp; Volonterio &amp; Artois" authorityYear="2009" box="[188,348,961,983]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" genus="Serrula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="768" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="acuta">
<emphasis box="[188,348,961,983]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">Serrula acuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: same locality as 
<taxonomicName box="[561,714,961,983]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" genus="Serrula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="768" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="maxillaria">
<emphasis box="[561,714,961,983]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">S. maxillaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="768" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="9.[164,779,1023,1198]" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">
<emphasis box="[164,363,1023,1044]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">Material studied:</emphasis>
Drawings from the living animals, except for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schockaert &amp; Curini-Galletti &amp; Ridder &amp; Volonterio &amp; Artois" authorityYear="2009" box="[285,380,1054,1075]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" genus="Serrula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="768" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="acuta">
<emphasis box="[285,380,1054,1075]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">S. acuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. One whole mount of each species (designated as 
<typeStatus box="[335,446,1084,1106]" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">holotypes</typeStatus>
, QM G 230108–230111). Sections of one individual of 
<taxonomicName box="[471,626,1115,1136]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" genus="Serrula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="768" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="byronensis">
<emphasis box="[471,626,1115,1136]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">S. byronensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of very poor quality, and without relevant information (except the epidermis) (UH 393).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="768" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[164,779,1238,1504]" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">
<emphasis box="[164,290,1238,1259]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">Etymology:</emphasis>
The genus name refers to the serrate end of the needles in two of the species (Latin 
<emphasis box="[691,772,1268,1289]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">serrula</emphasis>
: little saw). The species epithet of 
<taxonomicName box="[552,704,1299,1320]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" genus="Serrula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="768" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="byronensis">
<emphasis box="[552,704,1299,1320]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">S. byronensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
refers to the place where it has been found; that of 
<taxonomicName class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" genus="Serrula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="768" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="concharum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">S. concharum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
refers to the co-occurrence with many shells (Latin 
<emphasis box="[321,399,1391,1412]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">concha</emphasis>
: shell); the needles of 
<taxonomicName class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" genus="Serrula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="768" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="maxillaria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">S. maxillaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
show some resemblance to the maxillae of crustaceans; the needles of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schockaert &amp; Curini-Galletti &amp; Ridder &amp; Volonterio &amp; Artois" authorityYear="2009" box="[435,530,1452,1474]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" genus="Serrula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="768" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="acuta">
<emphasis box="[435,530,1452,1474]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">S. acuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are very slender and pointed (Latin 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schockaert &amp; Curini-Galletti &amp; Ridder &amp; Volonterio &amp; Artois" authorityYear="2009" box="[339,402,1483,1504]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" genus="Serrula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="768" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="acuta">
<emphasis box="[339,402,1483,1504]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">acuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: pointed).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="768" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[164,779,1544,1903]" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">
<emphasis box="[164,300,1545,1566]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">Description:</emphasis>
These four species are described from only one living individual of each species, and from the whole mounts. Therefore, our knowledge of a number of important characters is lacking. Nevertheless, we consider it worthwhile to describe them, hoping that more abundant material may be found in the future.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[164,779,1544,1903]" lastBlockId="9.[826,1442,839,1901]" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">
The four species are relatively small: only about 1-mm long. They have the usual anterior sensory bristles, but also have long bristles at the caudal end. 
<taxonomicName box="[164,326,1850,1871]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" genus="Serrula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="768" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="byron">
<emphasis box="[164,326,1850,1871]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">Serrula byron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also has prominent adhesive papillae (
<figureCitation box="[172,257,1881,1903]" captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="10.[806,885,1316,1335]" captionTargetBox="[857,1371,195,1286]" captionTargetId="figure-626@10.[871,1341,525,1090]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 13. Living specimens of the species of Serrula. A, Serrula byronensis sp. nov.; B, Serrula maxillaria sp. nov.; C, Serrula concharum sp. nov. Refer to the Appendix for a list of abbreviations." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4635064" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4635064/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">Figs 13</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[273,303,1881,1903]" captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="11.[164,243,1031,1050]" captionTargetBox="[385,1221,197,999]" captionTargetId="graphics-0@11.[385,1220,198,999]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figure 14. Posteriormost body part in live animals. A, Serrula byronensis sp. nov.; B, Serrula maxillaria sp. nov.; C, Serrula concharum sp. nov. Refer to the Appendix for a list of abbreviations." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4635066" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4635066/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">14</figureCitation>
). The precerebral gut diverticle reaches far in front of the statocyst in 
<taxonomicName box="[1174,1331,839,860]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" genus="Serrula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="768" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="concharum">
<emphasis box="[1174,1331,839,860]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">S. concharum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, whereas it ends roughly above the statocyst in 
<taxonomicName box="[1287,1441,869,891]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" genus="Serrula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="768" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="byronensis">
<emphasis box="[1287,1441,869,891]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">S. byronensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[885,1044,900,921]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" genus="Serrula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="768" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="maxillaria">
<emphasis box="[885,1044,900,921]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">S. maxillaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(and is unknown in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schockaert &amp; Curini-Galletti &amp; Ridder &amp; Volonterio &amp; Artois" authorityYear="2009" box="[1324,1426,900,922]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" genus="Serrula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="768" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="acuta">
<emphasis box="[1324,1426,900,922]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">S. acuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Cnidocysts were seen in the anterior part of the gut in 
<taxonomicName box="[826,979,961,983]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" genus="Serrula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="768" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="maxillaria">
<emphasis box="[826,979,961,983]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">S. maxillaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="768" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[826,1442,839,1901]" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">
The globular and ventrally directed pharynx is placed at the first quarter of the body; the ovaries, located anterior to the pharynx, are preceded by a single pair of testes. All vitellarian follicles are behind the pharynx, and the posteriormost follicles are found in front of the copulatory bursa in 
<taxonomicName box="[1230,1382,1145,1166]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" genus="Serrula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="768" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="byronensis">
<emphasis box="[1230,1382,1145,1166]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">S. byronensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and in front of the copulatory organ in the other species. The female pore is located at some distance behind the seminal vesicle (
<figureCitation box="[1064,1145,1237,1259]" captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="11.[164,243,1031,1050]" captionTargetBox="[385,1221,197,999]" captionTargetId="graphics-0@11.[385,1220,198,999]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figure 14. Posteriormost body part in live animals. A, Serrula byronensis sp. nov.; B, Serrula maxillaria sp. nov.; C, Serrula concharum sp. nov. Refer to the Appendix for a list of abbreviations." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4635066" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4635066/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
). The copulatory organ is directed forwards, with a small prostate vesicle on which the two needles are attached. 
<taxonomicName class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" genus="Serrula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="768" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="concharum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">Serrula concharum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a pair of seminal vesicles; the other species have an unpaired seminal vesicle. Only in 
<taxonomicName class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" genus="Serrula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="768" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="byron">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">S. byron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a prepenial copulatory bursa been observed, with a vagina just in front of the copulatory organ. We could not determine whether the vagina and the male pore are combined or not. As far as the whole mount reveals, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schockaert &amp; Curini-Galletti &amp; Ridder &amp; Volonterio &amp; Artois" authorityYear="2009" box="[1088,1186,1512,1534]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" genus="Serrula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="768" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="acuta">
<emphasis box="[1088,1186,1512,1534]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">S. acuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a single seminal vesicle, whereas a copulatory bursa is absent. Without sections, it cannot be said if a genitointestinal connection or a resorbing bursa is present.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[826,1442,839,1901]" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">
The hard parts of the copulatory organ (
<figureCitation box="[1354,1432,1634,1656]" captionStart="Figure 15" captionStartId="11.[164,243,1778,1797]" captionTargetBox="[166,1447,1193,1747]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figure 15. The needles and the muscular supports of the copulatory organ in the species of Serrula. A, Serrula byronensis sp. nov.; B, Serrula maxillaria sp. nov.; C, Serrula concharum sp. nov.; D, Serrula acuta sp. nov. Refer to the Appendix for a list of abbreviations." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4635068" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4635068/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
) consist of two spines that we interpret as the equivalent of the needles in the male atrium of the other representatives of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schockaert &amp; Curini-Galletti &amp; Ridder &amp; Volonterio &amp; Artois" authorityYear="2009" box="[1012,1164,1726,1748]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="768" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="family">Meidiamidae</taxonomicName>
. Except in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schockaert &amp; Curini-Galletti &amp; Ridder &amp; Volonterio &amp; Artois" authorityYear="2009" box="[1285,1377,1727,1748]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Meidiamidae" genus="Serrula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="768" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="acuta">
<emphasis box="[1285,1377,1727,1748]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="768">S. acuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, each of the two needles sits on a base, evidently formed by two muscles that ‘flank’ the prostate vesicle at either side. Because of the lack of sections, the hypothesis that these bases are muscles is yet to be confirmed. The form and size of the needles are given in the diagnoses.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
